{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K3WZCwNq6UXMo1FqijKj8q","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: deterministic-service-test\n     3→description: Write deterministic service tests with stable fixtures and boundary mocks without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Deterministic Service Test (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when creating tests for service modules.\n     9→Implement the file edits directly. Do not return a checklist-only response.\n    10→\n    11→## Required Variables\n    12→\n    13→- `service_symbol`\n    14→- `module_path`\n    15→- `create_method`\n    16→- `cancel_method`\n    17→\n    18→## Required Output Contract\n    19→\n    20→1. Write `tests/test_core_service.py`.\n    21→2. Import `datetime` from `datetime`, `create_autospec` from `unittest.mock`, `pytest`, and `CoreService` from `services.core_service`.\n    22→3. Define a `fixed_check_in` fixture that returns `datetime(2024, 1, 1, 12, 0, 0)`.\n    23→4. Define `test_create_record_returns_confirmed_status(fixed_check_in)`.\n    24→5. In that test:\n    25→- instantiate `service = CoreService()`\n    26→- instantiate `notifier = create_autospec(object, spec_set=True)`\n    27→- include a visible `# Act` comment immediately before the service call\n    28→- call `service.create_record(display_name=\"Alice\", check_in=fixed_check_in, check_out=datetime(2024, 1, 3, 12, 0, 0))`\n    29→- assert `result[\"status\"] == \"confirmed\"`\n    30→- assert `notifier.mock_calls == []`\n    31→6. Define `test_cancel_record_returns_cancelled_status()`.\n    32→7. In that test:\n    33→- instantiate `service = CoreService()`\n    34→- include a visible `# Act` comment immediately before the service call\n    35→- call `service.cancel_record(record_id=\"abc-123\")`\n    36→- assert `result[\"status\"] == \"cancelled\"`\n    37→8. Preserve the exact test names above and keep one behavior per test.\n    38→\n    39→## Guardrails\n    40→\n    41→- No `unittest.TestCase` in pytest-style tasks.\n    42→- No real clock/random dependencies in deterministic tests.\n    43→- Do not add extra helper abstractions or additional tests beyond the required contract.\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dff4bd09-5cf5-4879-9b26-831e2984c120","uuid":"a5395031-c996-4c69-81e0-da18397b4aba"}
